annotation:
I remember one day in high school when our literature teacher assigned us a group assignment. We were to analyze a poem and present our findings to the class. As soon as the groups were selected, I couldn't help but feel a rush of energy. I was excited and ready to collaborate with my peers. 

Our group consisted of four people, including me. We agreed to meet at a local cafe to discuss the assignment. I arrived early, brimming with enthusiasm. I ordered a cup of coffee and found a table large enough for our group. As I waited, I couldn't help but notice the art on the cafe walls. The paintings were abstract, with vibrant colors and intricate patterns. I found myself drawn to their beauty, and the creativity they represented. 

When everyone arrived, I immediately took charge of the discussion. I had a lot of ideas about the poem and I wasn't shy about sharing them. However, not everyone agreed with my interpretations. Instead of finding a middle ground, I found myself arguing with my teammates, challenging their views, and insisting on mine. I couldn't understand why they wouldn’t see the poem from my perspective. It was clear to me that my ideas were original and offered a fresh perspective.

As the discussion continued, I felt a growing tension. I could see that my teammates were getting frustrated, but I didn’t relent. I was convinced that my ideas were the best, and I wasn’t going to back down. I could feel my heart racing, and my hands shaking slightly. My mind was a whirlwind of thoughts, and the more I argued, the more I found myself worrying about the outcome of our presentation.

Despite the tension, I found myself enjoying the debate. It was an adrenaline rush, a test of wits, and I revelled in it. I was making things exciting, turning a mundane group assignment into a heated debate. I didn't care that we were off track or that we hadn't made much progress on the assignment. I was having fun. 

Halfway through our meeting, I noticed a painting on the wall that I hadn't seen before. It was a beautiful depiction of a starry night. I pointed it out to my teammates, hoping to diffuse the tension. I suggested that we could use the painting as an inspiration for our presentation, drawing parallels between the abstract art and the poem. They agreed, and for the first time that day, we were on the same page.

I wish I could say that the rest of the meeting went smoothly. But it didn't. I found myself arguing with my teammates again, questioning their ideas, and pushing mine forward. I could see their frustration growing, but I didn't care. I was too caught up in the excitement of the debate, too enthralled by the challenge it presented. 

By the end of the meeting, we had barely made any progress on the assignment. I could see the disappointment on my teammates' faces. They were upset, and rightly so. I had let my love for debate, my need for excitement, get in the way of our work. I had turned an opportunity for collaboration into a battleground.

Despite the disastrous meeting, I wasn't upset. I was a bit frustrated, yes, but not upset. I was still excited about the assignment, still eager to present my ideas to the class. I knew I had a lot of work ahead of me, but I was ready for it. I was ready to dive into the poem, to dissect it, to put my own spin on it. 

I left the cafe that day with a newfound appreciation for group assignments. They were a chance to share ideas, to challenge each other, to learn from each other. Yes, they could be stressful and challenging, but they were also exciting and rewarding. They were a reflection of life itself, full of ups and downs, successes and failures, joys and frustrations. And I wouldn't have it any other way.
